        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What does the filing say about common-control accounting, retrospective recasting of historical financials, and the mergers with xAI and X Holdings? What information is no longer observable or comparable relative to purchase accounting treatment? {{spacex_s1}}'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Common-Control Accounting, Retrospective Recasting, and the xAI/X Mergers\n\n## 1. The Merger Transactions\n\nTwo sequential share-exchange transactions were executed:\n\n| Transaction | Date | Acquirer | Target | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **X Merger** | March 28, 2025 | xAI | X Holdings Corp. and X.AI Corp. | Share exchange; X and X.AI Corp. became wholly-owned subsidiaries of xAI |\n| **xAI Merger** | February 2, 2026 | SpaceX | X.AI Holdings Corp. (xAI) | Share exchange; xAI became a wholly-owned subsidiary of SpaceX |\n\nX.AI Corp. began operations in March 2023; Twitter, Inc. was acquired by Elon Musk in October 2022. Both mergers were effected through share exchanges, and the combined transactions are referred to collectively as the "Mergers."\n\n---\n\n## 2. Common-Control Accounting Treatment\n\n### Basis for Common-Control Treatment\n\nThe Mergers were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control** rather than as business combinations under ASC 805 (purchase accounting). The justification stated in the filing is:\n\n> "Mr. Elon Musk had a controlling financial interest in the Company, xAI and X through his majority voting interest in each such entity during the years presented in these consolidated financial statements."\n\nBecause Musk held majority voting interests across all three entities throughout all periods presented, the transactions did not represent a change in ultimate control and therefore qualified for common-control pooling treatment.\n\n### Accounting Consequences\n\nThe filing specifies the following consequences of common-control treatment:\n\n1. **Retrospective combination at historical carrying amounts**: The consolidated financial statements reflect the combination of the net assets of SpaceX, xAI, and X at their **historical carrying amounts** for all periods presented — not at fair value.\n\n2. **No new goodwill or intangible assets**: The filing explicitly states: *"No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded."* This is a direct consequence of using historical book values rather than fair value purchase price allocation.\n\n3. **Elimination of intercompany transactions**: *"All historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation."* This means all transactions that occurred between SpaceX, xAI, and X during historical periods — such as commercial arrangements, service agreements, or funding transfers — are removed from the consolidated financials as if they never occurred.\n\n4. **Equity continuation and adjustment**: The capital stock and shareholders\' equity for all periods presented reflects:\n   - A continuation of historical SpaceX capital stock and shareholders\' equity, **combined with** the historical capital stock and shareholders\' equity of X and xAI, **as adjusted by the respective exchange ratios** used to effect the Mergers.\n   - The one exception is xAI\'s historical redeemable convertible preferred stock, which is discussed below.\n\n5. **Change in reporting entity**: The filing explicitly states: *"This presentation constitutes a change in reporting entity."* This is a significant accounting designation indicating that the reporting entity has fundamentally changed — the financial statements now encompass entities that were previously separate.\n\n6. **No separate financial statements provided**: The filing states: *"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."* This is a direct consequence of the retrospective combination — because the historical financials already include all entities, standalone statements would be redundant.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Retrospective Recasting of Historical Financials\n\nThe filing describes the retrospective recasting in multiple locations:\n\n> "The consolidated financial statements of SpaceX have been retrospectively recast for all periods presented to include (i) the historical results of X.AI Holdings Corp., which was acquired by SpaceX, effective February 2, 2026 (the \'xAI Merger\'), and X Holdings Corp. (\'X Holdings\'), which was acquired by xAI, effective March 28, 2025 (the \'X Merger\'), because these transactions were between entities under common control, and (ii) a five-for-one stock split of the Company\'s Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock, effective May 4, 2026 (the \'2026 Stock Split\')."\n\n### Scope of Retrospective Recasting\n\nThe recasting applies to:\n- **All periods presented** in the consolidated financial statements\n- The historical results of both xAI and X Holdings\n- All share and per share information (retroactively adjusted for the 2026 Stock Split)\n\n### Exchange Ratios Applied Retrospectively\n\nThe filing details the specific exchange ratios that were applied to retroactively convert historical share counts:\n\n**X Merger (March 28, 2025):**\n| Security Converted | Conversion Ratio | Into |\n|---|---|---|\n| X Holdings Corp. Common Stock (each class) | 2.776 shares | xAI Common Stock (same class), rounded down |\n| X.AI Corp. Common Stock (each class) | 1.000 share | xAI Common Stock (same class) |\n| X.AI Corp. Preferred Stock (each series, excluding shares held by X or its subsidiaries) | 1.000 share | xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock |\n\n**xAI Merger (February 2, 2026):**\n| Security Converted | Conversion Ratio | Into |\n|---|---|---|\n| xAI Common Stock (Class A, B, or Limited Voting) | 0.1433 SpaceX shares | SpaceX Common Stock |\n| xAI Common Stock (eligible service provider cash election) | $75.46 per share | Cash (pre-2026 Stock Split basis) |\n| xAI customer warrants (vested and unvested) | 0.1433 (cashless exercise) | SpaceX Class A Common Stock (fully vested) |\n| xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock | SpaceX Class B Common Stock per preferred share (pre-2026 Stock Split basis) | SpaceX Common Stock |\n\nThe filing states:\n\n> "As a result of the Mergers, all of X, X.AI Corp. and xAI Common Stock are being presented in the historical financial statements as if they had been converted into SpaceX Common Stock at the applicable exchange rate for all periods presented through the date of the xAI Merger."\n\n### The One Exception: xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock\n\nThe filing identifies a critical exception to the retrospective recasting. The xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was **not** retrospectively recast on an as-converted basis for periods prior to the xAI Merger Date. The filing explains:\n\n> "Because the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was legally outstanding during all historical periods prior to the xAI Merger and represented a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity, the conversion of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock into SpaceX Common Stock is recognized only as of the closing of the xAI Merger, and not retrospectively."\n\nAccordingly:\n- Historical consolidated balance sheets and statements of redeemable convertible preferred stock and shareholders\' equity reflect the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock **as outstanding xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock** consistent with its legal form and rights during those periods.\n- The conversion impact is presented **prospectively** in the period of the merger (Q1 2026), specifically in the consolidated statements of redeemable convertible preferred stock and shareholders\' equity for the three months ended March 31, 2026.\n- All shares of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock were converted to SpaceX common stock as part of the xAI Merger and are presented as such **from the date of the xAI Merger forward**.\n\n---\n\n## 4. What Information Is No Longer Observable or Comparable Relative to Purchase Accounting Treatment\n\nUnder purchase accounting (ASC 805), an acquirer would record the acquired entity\'s assets and liabilities at **fair value**, recognize **goodwill** for the excess of consideration over fair value of net assets, recognize **identifiable intangible assets**, and include the acquiree\'s results only **from the acquisition date forward**. The use of common-control accounting instead of purchase accounting means the following information is **no longer observable or comparable**:\n\n### a. Fair Value of Acquired Net Assets\nUnder purchase accounting, X\'s and xAI\'s tangible and intangible assets and liabilities would have been recorded at fair value at the acquisition date. Under common-control accounting, they are recorded at **historical carrying amounts**. The fair values of X\'s platform, user base, brand, technology infrastructure, and xAI\'s AI models, computational infrastructure, and intellectual property are **not reflected** in the consolidated financial statements and cannot be derived from them.\n\n### b. Goodwill\nThe filing explicitly states that **no new goodwill was recorded**. Under purchase accounting, the excess of the purchase consideration over the fair value of identifiable net assets would have been recorded as goodwill. Because the mergers were structured as share exchanges among commonly controlled entities, the implied purchase price premium — and any resulting goodwill — is **not observable**. An investor cannot determine what premium, if any, was effectively paid for X or xAI.\n\n### c. Identifiable Intangible Assets\nUnder purchase accounting, identifiable intangibles such as X\'s trade name, user relationships, advertiser relationships, developed technology, and xAI\'s AI models and algorithms would have been separately recognized at fair value and amortized over their useful lives. Under common-control accounting, **no new intangible assets were recorded**. These assets remain embedded within the historical carrying amounts of the acquired entities and are **not separately identifiable**.\n\n### d. Standalone Financial Performance of xAI and X\nBecause the financial statements are retrospectively combined for all periods, and because the filing explicitly states that **separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided**, an investor cannot:\n- Determine the standalone revenue, expenses, or net income/loss of xAI or X for any historical period\n- Assess the individual profitability or growth trajectory of the AI business versus the social media platform\n- Compare pre-merger standalone performance to post-merger combined performance\n- Evaluate whether the mergers created or destroyed value on a standalone basis\n\n### e. Intercompany Transaction History\nThe filing states that **all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation**. This means that any commercial arrangements, service agreements, data-sharing arrangements, compute provisioning, advertising arrangements, or funding transfers between SpaceX, xAI, and X during historical periods are **not visible** in the consolidated financials. An investor cannot assess the nature, volume, or economics of these inter-entity relationships prior to formal combination.\n\nNote: Transactions with **external** related parties (such as Tesla and The Boring Company) remain visible because those entities are not part of the consolidated group. For example, the filing discloses that xAI obtained goods and services from Tesla of $191 million in 2024 and $506 million in 2025, and X Holdings had advertising revenue from Tesla of $0.5 million in 2024 and $4 million in 2025.\n\n### f. Fair Value Step-Up and Its Effect on Future Depreciation/Amortization\nUnder purchase accounting, the fair value step-up in acquired assets would have increased the depreciation and amortization expense in future periods. Under common-control accounting, depreciation and amortization continue to be based on historical carrying amounts. The financial statements therefore do **not reflect** the higher depreciation/amortization that would have resulted from purchase accounting, making future expense trends **not comparable** to what they would have been under purchase accounting.\n\n### g. Purchase Price Allocation\nUnder purchase accounting, a purchase price allocation would have been disclosed showing how the total consideration was allocated among assets acquired, liabilities assumed, goodwill, and intangible assets. Under common-control accounting, **no purchase price allocation is provided** because the transaction is accounted for at historical carrying amounts. The implied valuation of the share exchanges (based on the exchange ratios and the value of SpaceX shares) is **not reconciled** to the net assets received.\n\n### h. Pro Forma Combined Results vs. Actual Combined Results\nUnder purchase accounting, the filing would have included pro forma financial information showing what the combined entity\'s results would have been (with fair value adjustments) as if the merger had occurred at the beginning of the earliest period presented. Under common-control accounting, the **actual** historical combined results (at historical carrying amounts, without fair value adjustments) are presented instead. While this provides actual combined data, it is **not comparable** to what pro forma purchase-accounting results would have shown, because it lacks the fair value adjustments, goodwill amortization, and intangible asset amortization that would have been included.\n\n### i. Acquisition-Date Balance Sheet\nUnder purchase accounting, an acquisition-date balance sheet would show the fair values of assets acquired and liabilities assumed. Under common-control accounting, the balance sheet simply **continues** the historical carrying amounts of all entities, with equity adjusted for exchange ratios. There is no "step-up" or revaluation at the acquisition date, so the investor **cannot observe** the fair value balance sheet of the acquired entities at the merger date.\n\n### j. Earn-Out or Contingent Consideration\nThe filing does not discuss contingent consideration or earn-outs, but under purchase accounting, any contingent consideration would have been recognized at fair value. Under common-control accounting, such arrangements (if any existed) would be accounted for differently and may **not be observable** in the same way.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Summary of Key Distinctions\n\n| Aspect | Purchase Accounting (ASC 805) | Common-Control Accounting (As Applied) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Asset/liability measurement | Fair value at acquisition date | Historical carrying amounts |\n| Goodwill | Recognized for excess of consideration over fair value of net assets | **Not recorded** |\n| Identifiable intangibles | Recognized at fair value, amortized over useful lives | **Not recorded** |\n| Reporting periods | Acquiree included from acquisition date forward | **Retrospectively combined for all periods presented** |\n| Intercompany transactions | Eliminated only from acquisition date forward | **Eliminated for all historical periods** |\n| Separate financial statements of acquiree | Typically provided or pro forma disclosed | **Not provided** |\n| Purchase price allocation | Disclosed | **Not applicable/not disclosed** |\n| Pro forma financial information | Required | **Not provided** (actual combined results presented instead) |\n| Change in reporting entity | Not typically designated | **Explicitly designated as a change in reporting entity** |\n| Depreciation/amortization going forward | Reflects fair value step-up | **Based on historical carrying amounts** |\n| xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock | Would be fair-valued/converted at acquisition | **Not retrospectively recast; presented in legal form until xAI Merger Date, then converted prospectively** |\n\nThe net effect is that the consolidated financial statements present a combined entity whose historical financials reflect the actual historical carrying amounts and operating results of SpaceX, xAI, and X as if they had always been combined — but without any fair value revaluation, goodwill recognition, intangible asset identification, or purchase price allocation that would have provided insight into the economic value assigned to the acquired businesses through the share exchange transactions.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
