    final_answer='## What Historical Information Is No Longer Observable Under Common-Control Accounting vs. Purchase Accounting\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) retrospectively recasts the consolidated financial statements to include xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all periods presented, because Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X throughout the periods presented. The filing explicitly states: *"This presentation constitutes a change in reporting entity."*\n\nBecause the Mergers were accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control rather than as business combinations under ASC 805 (purchase accounting), the following historical information is **no longer observable or comparable** relative to what purchase accounting would have produced:\n\n### 1. Fair Value of Acquired Net Assets\nUnder purchase accounting, X\'s and xAI\'s assets and liabilities would have been recorded at **fair value** at the acquisition date. Under common-control accounting, they are recorded at **historical carrying amounts**. The fair values of X\'s platform, user base, brand, technology infrastructure, and xAI\'s AI models, computational infrastructure, and intellectual property are not reflected and cannot be derived from the consolidated financials.\n\n### 2. Goodwill\nThe filing explicitly states: *"No new goodwill or other intangible assets have been recorded."* Under purchase accounting, the excess of consideration over the fair value of identifiable net assets would have been recorded as goodwill. The implied purchase price premium paid for X or xAI — and any resulting goodwill — is therefore **not observable**.\n\n### 3. Identifiable Intangible Assets\nUnder purchase accounting, identifiable intangibles (e.g., X\'s trade name, user/advertiser relationships, developed technology; xAI\'s AI models and algorithms) would have been separately recognized at fair value and amortized. Under common-control accounting, **no new intangible assets were recorded**. These assets remain embedded within historical carrying amounts and are **not separately identifiable**.\n\n### 4. Standalone Financial Performance of xAI and X\nThe filing states: *"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."* As a result, an investor cannot observe:\n- Standalone revenue, expenses, or net income/loss of xAI or X for any historical period\n- The individual profitability or growth trajectory of the AI business versus the social media platform\n- Pre-merger standalone performance versus post-merger combined performance\n- Whether the mergers created or destroyed value on a standalone basis\n\n### 5. Intercompany Transaction History\nThe filing states that *"all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation"* (and Note 2 confirms: *"All intercompany balances and transactions have been eliminated in consolidation"*). Under purchase accounting, intercompany transactions would only be eliminated from the acquisition date forward. Under common-control accounting, they are eliminated for **all historical periods**, so any commercial arrangements, service agreements, data-sharing, compute provisioning, advertising arrangements, or funding transfers between SpaceX, xAI, and X during historical periods are **not visible** in the consolidated financials.\n\n(Note: Transactions with external related parties such as Tesla and The Boring Company remain visible — e.g., xAI obtained goods/services from Tesla of $191M in 2024 and $506M in 2025; X had advertising revenue from Tesla of $0.5M in 2024 and $4M in 2025.)\n\n### 6. Fair Value Step-Up and Its Effect on Future Depreciation/Amortization\nUnder purchase accounting, the fair value step-up in acquired assets would have increased future depreciation and amortization expense. Under common-control accounting, depreciation and amortization continue to be based on historical carrying amounts, so future expense trends are **not comparable** to what they would have been under purchase accounting.\n\n### 7. Purchase Price Allocation\nUnder purchase accounting, a purchase price allocation would have been disclosed showing how total consideration was allocated among assets acquired, liabilities assumed, goodwill, and intangibles. Under common-control accounting, **no purchase price allocation is provided**. The implied valuation of the share exchanges (based on the disclosed exchange ratios and SpaceX share values) is **not reconciled** to the net assets received.\n\n### 8. Pro Forma Combined Results (with Fair Value Adjustments)\nUnder purchase accounting, the filing would have included pro forma financial information showing combined results as if the merger had occurred at the beginning of the earliest period presented, including fair value adjustments. Under common-control accounting, the **actual** historical combined results (at historical carrying amounts, without fair value adjustments) are presented instead. While this provides actual combined data, it is **not comparable** to what pro forma purchase-accounting results would have shown.\n\n### 9. Acquisition-Date Balance Sheet (Fair Value)\nUnder purchase accounting, an acquisition-date balance sheet would show the fair values of assets acquired and liabilities assumed. Under common-control accounting, the balance sheet simply **continues** the historical carrying amounts of all entities, with equity adjusted for exchange ratios. There is no "step-up" or revaluation at the acquisition date, so the investor **cannot observe** the fair value balance sheet of the acquired entities at the merger date.\n\n### 10. The xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock Exception\nThe filing identifies one notable exception to the retrospective recasting. The xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was **not** retrospectively recast on an as-converted basis for periods prior to the xAI Merger Date. The filing explains: *"Because the xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was legally outstanding during all historical periods prior to the xAI Merger and represented a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity, the conversion of xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock into SpaceX Common Stock is recognized only as of the closing of the xAI Merger, and not retrospectively."* This means the conversion impact is presented **prospectively** in Q1 2026, and the historical equity structure does not reflect the as-converted SpaceX share count for that security.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Item | Purchase Accounting (ASC 805) | Common-Control Accounting (As Applied) |\n|---|---|---|\n| Asset/liability measurement | Fair value at acquisition date | Historical carrying amounts |\n| Goodwill | Recognized | **Not recorded** |\n| Identifiable intangibles | Recognized at fair value, amortized | **Not recorded** |\n| Reporting periods for acquiree | From acquisition date forward | **Retrospectively combined for all periods** |\n| Intercompany transactions | Eliminated from acquisition date forward | **Eliminated for all historical periods** |\n| Separate financial statements of acquiree | Typically provided or pro forma disclosed | **Not provided** |\n| Purchase price allocation | Disclosed | **Not applicable/not disclosed** |\n| Pro forma financial information | Required | **Not provided** (actual combined results instead) |\n| Acquisition-date fair value balance sheet | Disclosed | **Not observable** |\n| Future depreciation/amortization | Reflects fair value step-up | **Based on historical carrying amounts** |\n| xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock | Would be fair-valued/converted at acquisition | **Not retrospectively recast; converted prospectively at xAI Merger Date** |\n\nThe net effect is that the consolidated financial statements present a combined entity whose historical financials reflect the actual historical carrying amounts and operating results of SpaceX, xAI, and X as if they had always been combined — but without any fair value revaluation, goodwill recognition, intangible asset identification, purchase price allocation, or standalone acquiree financials that would have provided insight into the economic value assigned to the acquired businesses through the share exchange transactions.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Notes to Consolidated Financial Statements, Merger Accounting discussion, and Note 2 (Summary of Significant Accounting Policies)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
